Sent: Tuesday, May 20, 2003 11:51 PM
Subject: [T2] What causes a 30# compression reading?


> My 1979 2000 engine started misfiring and I troubleshot down to a 30#
> compression on the #4 cylinder.  Now I suspect that either the piston ring
or
> valve seat has failed.  I heard that type II engines are known for valve
seats
> to fail.  Is this true and how will I know when I look at it?

Failing valve seats ?  Where did you hear that :) ???
Try this- Unbolt the rocker shafts from the offending cylinder
head and put a straight-edge across the ends of the valve stems.
You don't need a leak-down test, it's time to remove the head
for a look after it gets down to about 85 psi.
Dave \X/
